Tasks for homework 3¶

  1. Calculate the predictions for some selected observations

  2. Then, calculate the decomposition of these predictions with LIME using the package of choice, e.g. in Python: lime, dalex, in R: iml, localModel.

  3. Compare LIME for various observations in the dataset. How stable are these explanations?

  4. Compare LIME with the explanations obtained using SHAP. What are the main differences between them?

  5. Compare LIME between at least two different models. Are there any systematic differences across many observations?

  6. Comment on the results obtained in (3), (4) and (5)

Report¶

Based on the dataset from the previous homeworks, I've trained xgboost model. I've decided to split dataset into two parts: math and portugese as the factors for achieving good grades my be different in this cases.

For the math dataset I've obtained following results:

  • recall: 1.0
  • precision: 0.142857
  • f1: 0.25
  • accuracy: 0.333333
  • auc: 0.491981

and for the portuguese dataset:

  • recall: 1.0
  • precision: 0.333333
  • f1: 0.5
  • accuracy: 0.5
  • auc: 0.491133.

For analysing LIME explanaitions, I've chosen two observations for each dataset - one with correct prediction and one with wrong prediction.

  • stability of LIME for the same example
  • stability of LIME for various examples.

For the first case we got following results:

Top 3 features are the same in 3 out of 4 examples, although values are different.

For the wrong prediction we got:

Again top 3 features are rather stable.

For the second case I've randomly chosen 4 obervations. With random seed we got following results:

With constant seed:

With contant seed LIME results are stable for randomly chosen observations.

From that experiment we got some important morale -- when explaining the model with LIME we have to take into consideration its instability.

The next step is comparing LIME explanaitions with SHAP:

  • Math dataset, correct prediction

Selected features are different from those selected by LIME. First feature from SHAP is the third in LIME. Failures feature which is the first feature in LIME does not appear in the SHAP plot at all.

Math dataset, wrong prediction: similarly to the correct prediction.

For the portuguese dataset:

For the portuguese dataset selected features are quite similar in both methods.

The last but not least, we were supposed to compare LIME explanaitions across different models. The second model I've chosen is SVM.

For the math dataset we got following LIME features

Chosen features and their values are drastically different than the one's from xgboost model. We can see that the most influential feature in SVM model is absences. The other attributes don't have much influence on the prediction.

For the portuguese model we have:

For portuguese dataset the features also differ from the xgboost model, but values of the first feature are not as drastic as in the math dataset case.

Data preparation¶

In [6]:
df_math = pd.read_csv('/content/data/Maths.csv')
df_port = pd.read_csv('/content/data/Portuguese.csv')
In [7]:
def get_one_hot_columns(df):
  one_hot_columns = []
  for column in df.columns:
    if df[column].dtype == 'object':
      one_hot_columns.append(column)
  return one_hot_columns
In [8]:
df_math = pd.get_dummies(df_math, columns=get_one_hot_columns(df_math), drop_first=True)
df_port = pd.get_dummies(df_port, columns=get_one_hot_columns(df_port), drop_first=True)
In [9]:
df_math = df_math[df_math['G3'] != 20]
df_math = df_math[df_math['G3'] != 4]
df_port = df_port[df_port['G3'] != 1]
df_port = df_port[df_port['G3'] != 5]
In [10]:
X_math = df_math.copy()
X_math = X_math.drop(['G3', 'G2', 'G1'], axis=1)
y_math = df_math['G3']

X_port = df_port.copy()
X_port = X_port.drop(['G3', 'G2', 'G1'], axis=1)
y_port = df_port['G3']
In [11]:
prev_math = list(set(y_math))
prev_port = list(set(y_port))
In [12]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()
y_math = le.fit_transform(y_math)
y_port = le.fit_transform(y_port)
In [13]:
encoded_math = list(set(y_math))
encoded_port = list(set(y_port))
In [14]:
def label_encoding(prev, encoded):
  encoded_to_prev_label = {}
  for p, e in zip(prev, encoded):
    encoded_to_prev_label[e] = p
  return encoded_to_prev_label
In [15]:
encoded_to_prev_label_math = label_encoding(prev_math, encoded_math)
encoded_to_prev_label_port = label_encoding(prev_port, encoded_port)
In [16]:
X_math_train, X_math_test, y_math_train, y_math_test = train_test_split(X_math, y_math, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y_math)
X_port_train, X_port_test, y_port_train, y_port_test = train_test_split(X_port, y_port, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y_port)

def pf_xgboost_classifier(model, df):
    return np.argmax(model.predict_proba(df),axis=-1)

explainer = dalex.Explainer(xgb_math, X_math_test, y_math_test, predict_function=pf_xgboost_classifier, label='xgboost')
